<paper id="1482673219"><title>Secret-Key Agreement without Public-Key Cryptography</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="massachusetts institute of technology" id="2178157365">Frank Thomson Leighton</author><author org="massachusetts institute of technology" id="699581604">Silvio Micali</author></authors><n_citation>116</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1497619716</reference><reference>1822822445</reference><reference>2105514582</reference><reference>2117362057</reference><reference>2146973388</reference><reference>2156186849</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48329-2_39</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.62554">Financial cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.59644">PKCS #1</keyword><keyword weight="0.61291">Cryptography law</keyword><keyword weight="0.45469">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.60089">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.45393">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.61658">Neural cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.43582">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.61512">Strong cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.60003">Public-key cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.63408">Key (cryptography)</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper, we describe novel approaches to secret-key agreement. Our schemes are not based on public-key cryptography nor number theory. They are extremely efficient implemented in software or make use of very simple uuexpensive hardware. Our technology is particularly well-suited for use in cryptographic scenarios like those of the Clipper Chip, the recent encryption proposal put forward by the Clinton Administration.</abstract></paper>